# ============================================================================
# M3M Brabus — environment variables
#
# Copy to `.env` (git-ignored) for local work, and set the same names in the
# Vercel project's Environment Variables panel for deploys.
#
#   cp .env.example .env
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# READ THIS BEFORE ADDING ANYTHING
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Vite INLINES every variable whose name begins with `VITE_` directly into the
# JavaScript bundle at build time. It is not a runtime lookup and it is not
# hidden. Any visitor can open devtools, search the bundle and read the value.
# Anyone can also read it in the prerendered HTML, and — because Vercel serves
# the built assets publicly — in the deployment itself.
#
# Therefore:
#
#   *** NO SECRET MAY EVER CARRY THE `VITE_` PREFIX. ***
#
# No API key with write access, no CRM token, no OAuth client secret, no
# Sheets service-account credential, no SMTP password. If a value would cause
# harm in a stranger's hands, it does not belong in this file, in `.env`, or in
# a static bundle of any kind — it belongs behind a server. This project has
# exactly one place where server-side secrets can live: the Google Apps Script
# deployment in `server/apps-script/`, whose configuration is edited in the
# Apps Script editor and never travels through this repository.
#
# Variables WITHOUT the `VITE_` prefix are visible only to the Node build
# process. They never reach the browser. They are still not a good place for
# real secrets in a public repository, but they are safe from visitors.
#
# Leaking a key through a `VITE_` variable is the single most common way a
# static site is compromised. It has happened to better-run projects than this
# one. Please do not be the reason it happens here.
# ============================================================================


# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 1. READ BY THE APPLICATION TODAY
#    These are the only VITE_ variables any shipped code actually reads.
#    Verified by grepping `import.meta.env` across src/.
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Google Analytics 4 measurement ID.
#   Read by: src/lib/analytics.js
#   Public by design — a GA4 measurement ID is printed into every page that
#   uses gtag.js on every site on the web. It is an identifier, not a
#   credential.
#   Where to get it: analytics.google.com → Admin → Data Streams → your web
#   stream → "Measurement ID". Format: G-XXXXXXXXXX.
#   Leave EMPTY to switch analytics off entirely: initAnalytics() and every
#   track() call become no-ops, so nothing breaks in dev or during prerender.
VITE_GA_ID=


# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 2. BUILD-TIME ONLY (Node process — never reaches the browser)
#    No VITE_ prefix, deliberately.
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Absolute path to a Chrome/Chromium binary for the prerender step.
#   Read by: scripts/prerender.mjs
#   REQUIRED anywhere that is not a Mac with Google Chrome installed at the
#   default location — which includes every CI runner and every Linux machine.
#   `npm run build:static` exits non-zero if this path does not exist, so a
#   missing binary fails the build instead of silently shipping an unrendered
#   site.
#   macOS default (used when unset):
#     /Applications/Google Chrome.app/Contents/MacOS/Google Chrome
#   Debian/Ubuntu:  /usr/bin/google-chrome-stable
#   Puppeteer-installed Chrome: run `npx @puppeteer/browsers install chrome`
#     and use the path it prints.
CHROME_PATH=

# Port for the temporary static server the prerenderer drives Chrome against.
#   Read by: scripts/prerender.mjs   Default: 4179
#   Only worth setting if 4179 is already in use on the build machine.
PRERENDER_PORT=

# Canonical origin written into dist/sitemap.xml.
#   Read by: scripts/sitemap.mjs     Default: https://m3m-brabus.com
#   No trailing slash. Set this on a staging deployment so the staging sitemap
#   does not advertise production URLs.
#   NOTE: this does NOT change the canonical/Open Graph URLs in the pages
#   themselves — those come from SITE_URL in src/components/ui/Seo.jsx, which
#   is a hard-coded constant, not an environment variable.
SITE_URL=


# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 3. SERVER-SIDE ONLY — the CMS OAuth relay (api/auth.js, api/callback.js)
#
#    These are the ONLY real secrets in the project, and the only place one can
#    safely live. `api/` deploys as Vercel serverless functions, which run on
#    Vercel's servers rather than in the visitor's browser, so `process.env`
#    there is genuinely private.
#
#    Set these in the Vercel dashboard (Project → Settings → Environment
#    Variables). None of them may EVER be given a VITE_ prefix — a VITE_
#    prefix would take the client secret out of the server and print it into
#    the public bundle, handing every visitor write access to the repository.
#
#    Read by: api/_shared.js
#    Full walkthrough: docs/CMS-GUIDE.md
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# GitHub OAuth App client ID.
#   Public in practice — it appears in the URL the browser is redirected to.
#   Kept here without a VITE_ prefix anyway, because only the serverless
#   function needs it.
#   Where to get it: github.com → Settings → Developer settings → OAuth Apps →
#   New OAuth App.
#     Homepage URL:               https://<your-domain>
#     Authorization callback URL: https://<your-domain>/api/callback
GITHUB_CLIENT_ID=

# GitHub OAuth App client secret.
#   *** A GENUINE SECRET. *** It is exchanged for a user access token entirely
#   server-side and is never logged, never returned to the browser, and never
#   committed. Anyone holding it can obtain tokens that write to the
#   repository. Rotate it in GitHub if it is ever exposed, and rotate it when
#   anyone with access to the Vercel project leaves.
GITHUB_CLIENT_SECRET=

# OAuth scope requested from GitHub.
#   Default: "repo" (works for a private repository).
#   Use "public_repo" if the repository is public — it is the narrower grant
#   and an editor's token should not carry more authority than the job needs.
GITHUB_OAUTH_SCOPE=

# Extra origins allowed to receive the token, comma-separated.
#   The relay defaults to postMessage-ing the token only to the origin serving
#   /admin, i.e. this deployment. Add an origin here only to run the CMS
#   against a local dev server, e.g. http://localhost:5173.
#   Every entry widens who can be handed a repository-write token. Keep it
#   empty in production.
ALLOWED_CMS_ORIGINS=

# Override the OAuth callback URL.
#   Only needed when the deployment host differs from the callback host
#   registered on the GitHub OAuth App — a custom domain in front of a
#   *.vercel.app deployment, typically.
#   Default: https://<this deployment>/api/callback
OAUTH_REDIRECT_URI=


# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 4. CI SECRETS — GitHub Actions, not this file
#
#    The production build runs in .github/workflows/deploy.yml, because the
#    prerender step needs a Chrome binary that Vercel's build image does not
#    have. Its credentials live in the repository's Actions secrets, never in
#    .env and never in the Vercel dashboard:
#
#      VERCEL_TOKEN       genuine secret — deploy rights on the account/team
#      VERCEL_ORG_ID      identifier, from `vercel link`
#      VERCEL_PROJECT_ID  identifier, from `vercel link`
#
#    Optional repository *variable* (not a secret):
#      SITE_URL           origin written into sitemap.xml
#
#    Note the workflow copies `.vercel/.env.<target>.local` (produced by
#    `vercel pull`) to `.env.local` before building. That is what makes a
#    VITE_ variable configured in the Vercel dashboard reach the bundle even
#    though Vite, not Vercel, performs the build.
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------


# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 5. NOT READ BY ANY CODE
#    Documented so the name is agreed in advance. Setting it today does
#    nothing.
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Maintenance / holding page switch.
#   src/pages/MaintenancePage.jsx is written and complete, but nothing renders
#   it — App.jsx does not import it. The file's header comment gives the exact
#   two lines to add. Once added, this flag is read at BUILD time, so turning
#   maintenance mode on or off requires a redeploy. That is a property of a
#   static site, not an oversight. The page also cannot return HTTP 503;
#   Vercel serves it as 200.
#   Public by design (it is a boolean, visible in the bundle).
#   Set to the string "1" to enable.
# VITE_MAINTENANCE=


# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 6. THINGS PEOPLE LOOK FOR HERE AND WILL NOT FIND
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Lead endpoint.
#   The Google Apps Script URL is hard-coded as ENDPOINT in src/lib/leads.js,
#   not configurable. One consequence worth knowing: local dev, preview
#   deployments and production all post to the same live endpoint, so a test
#   submission writes a real row and mails the real sales inbox. See
#   docs/SETUP.md §4.

# Vercel Web Analytics / Speed Insights.
#   Not installed — neither @vercel/analytics nor @vercel/speed-insights is in
#   package.json. Web Analytics is switched on from the Vercel dashboard and
#   injects its own script; it needs no ID and no variable from us. There is no
#   such thing as a "Vercel analytics ID" to paste here.
#   The VERCEL_* variables (VERCEL_ENV, VERCEL_GIT_COMMIT_SHA, …) are injected
#   into the build environment automatically. Do not set them by hand.

# Search Console / Bing verification.
#   Not environment variables. Verify by DNS TXT record — it survives
#   redeploys and covers every subdomain — or drop the provider's HTML file
#   into public/.

# CRM API credentials (Salesforce, Zoho, HubSpot, …).
#   DO NOT ADD THEM AS VITE_ VARIABLES. A CRM write key in the client bundle
#   is published to every visitor, who can then write whatever they like into
#   your CRM. The supported integration path is Google Sheet → CRM, driven
#   from the Apps Script side or by the CRM's own Sheets connector, where the
#   credential stays server-side. See docs/CRM-FIELD-MAPPING.md §6.

# ------------------------------------------------------------
# Backend (server/) — optional. When set, the CTA forms post to the Node
# backend (which saves to Neon + forwards to Google Sheets) instead of posting
# to Apps Script directly. Leave unset to keep the original direct-Sheets flow.
# NOTE: VITE_ vars are inlined into the public bundle — this is a URL, not a
# secret, so that is fine. Point it at your deployed backend origin (no path).
# ------------------------------------------------------------
VITE_API_URL=https://your-backend-host.example.com
